### Logic Discrepancy & Onboarding Override Risk
**Risk:** The comment states that a fresh incoming invite outranks a stale half-done wizard unless the incoming invite matches the pending code. However, the guard check `if (params?.invite ...)` was deleted entirely. As a result, `getPendingOnboarding()` will unconditionally resume any stored incomplete wizard, ignoring any new invite link passed via deep link parameters.

**Suggested Fix:**
```typescript
    React.useEffect(() => {
        let mounted = true;
        (async () => {
            const pending = await getPendingOnboarding();
            if (!pending || !mounted) return;
            const incomingInvite = params?.invite || (incomingUrl && incomingUrl.includes('invite='));
            if (incomingInvite && pending.inviteCode !== params?.invite) return;
            const stored = await loadIdentity();
            if (!stored) {
                await clearPendingOnboarding();
                return;
            }
            if (!mounted) return;
            // ...
```

### Callsign Stale Value & Registration Mismatch
**Risk:** If `storedIdentity` exists, `identity` reuses `storedIdentity` (line 329). If the user edits their callsign on screen before tapping Create, `identity.callsign` remains set to `storedIdentity.callsign` instead of the newly entered `callsign.trim()`. Passing `identity.callsign` to `redeemInvite` registers the old stored callsign on the node, while `setPendingOnboarding` stores the new `callsign.trim()`, causing identity metadata desynchronization.

**Suggested Fix:**
```typescript
            const identity = storedIdentity 
                ? { ...storedIdentity, callsign: callsign.trim() } 
                : await createIdentity(callsign.trim());
            setPendingIdentity(identity);
            setPendingInviteCode(parsedCode);

            // Redeem invite on node IMMEDIATELY so member is registered right away
            try {
                await redeemInvite(parsedCode, identity.callsign, identity);
            } catch (redeemErr: any) {
                // ...
```

### Critical UX & Navigation Loop in PWA
**Risk:** `isTrampoline` is initialized to `true` by default. When a user opens the PWA with an invite link or enters an invite code, `useEffect` executes `window.location.href = nativeDeepLink`. Browsers cannot catch custom protocol scheme navigation failures in a JS `try/catch` block. Consequently, web-only users will experience immediate navigation failure or error popups. Furthermore, because `inviteCode` is in the dependency array, setting `window.location.href` triggers on input change while typing.

**Suggested Fix:**
```typescript
    useEffect(() => {
        // Only trigger deep link trampoline on initial load if explicitly flagged and URL param exists
        const urlParams = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search);
        const hasUrlInvite = urlParams.has('invite');
        if (isTrampoline && hasUrlInvite && inviteCode) {
            const nativeDeepLink = `beanpool://welcome?invite=${encodeURIComponent(inviteCode)}&server=${encodeURIComponent(window.location.origin)}`;
            window.location.href = nativeDeepLink;
        }
    }, [isTrampoline]);
```

### Duplicate Keypair Generation on Retry
**Risk:** In `handleCreate()`, `createIdentity(trimmedCallsign)` is called before attempting `redeemInvite`. If `redeemInvite` fails due to a network glitch or server error, the error is thrown and caught by `handleCreate`'s outer catch block. If the user taps "Create" again, a brand new `BeanPoolIdentity` keypair is generated, abandoning the previous keypair.

**Suggested Fix:**
```typescript
            const identity = pendingIdentity || await createIdentity(trimmedCallsign);
            setPendingIdentity(identity);
            setPendingInviteCode(trimmedCode);
```
